n</b>, habitational names based on Dutch <i>kruis</i> ‘cross’ (compare   Crusan   and   Kruis  )."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Crepon de Normandie was born about 0974, in Crépy, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Osulf Fil Frane de Plessie Seigneur De Belveir. She died about 1028, in Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, France, at the age of 56, and was buried in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 0974–about 1028":"umbes 0974–umbes 1028","0979–1067":"0979–1067",